<HEADLINE>
THE GOVERNMENT TO ASSIST ASIA PACIFIC BROADBAND TELECOM
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei  Jan.  17 (CNA) 01/18/07  11:10:39 (By Y.C. Jou)
</P>
<P>
The government is to assist Asia Pacific Broadband  Telecom
(ABPT)  in dealing with financial  problems associated with the
Rebar Asia Pacific Group crisis, the Ministry of Economic Affairs
(MOEA) announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Semi-State Small Business Integrated Assistance Foundation
will be joined by independent accountants in conducting overall
accounting checks for the company, MOEA Vice Minister Shih Yen-
Shiang and National Communications Commission Vice Chairperson
Howard Shyr said at a press conference Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Shih said government officials, scholars and representatives for
the state shareholdings of the APBT will meet to draw up
governance plans for the company, including a reorganization of
its board of directors and board of supervisors.
</P>
<P>
A reorganization of the boards of directors and supervisors has
become the consensus position, though there's still no timetable
set, " Shih Yen-Shiang said. He stated that APBT Vice Chairman
Wang Lin-tai reacted positively to discussions of the
reorganziation issue.
</P>
<P>
Among  APBT's  33 board  members,  7 represent  the state
shareholdings.
</P>
<P>
The MOEA said the business of the ABPT remained normal and that
the government move was to further ensure its healthy operations
and to protect the rights of employees and consumers.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors investigating the Rebar scandal Monday searched the
ABPT and found that Wang You-theng, head of the Rebar Group, had
channeled vast sums out of the company, causing great losses to
its investors.
</P>
<P>
The ABPT,  granted special permission  to operate  in the
telecommunication field Jan. 2001, has capitalization of NT$65.68
billion and employs 1,383 people. Several state-run companies,
and companies in which the state has invested, are among its
shareholders , including Mega International Commercial Bank and
China Steel. The former has an investment of NT$2.1 billion and
the latter NT$1.2 billion in the APBT.
</P>
